  "text": "Dynamic analysis presents a scalable alternative to static analysis for models with nonlinear dynamics. The basic procedure for dynamic safety verification has three building blocks: (a) a simulation engine, (b) a generalization or bloating procedure, and (c) a satisfiability checker. The simulation engine generates validated simulations of the model with some rigorous error bounds. The generalization procedure uses additional model information to over-approximate bounded-time reach sets from the simulations. This additional model information could be, for example, statically computed Lipschitz constants [CITATION_1] , contraction metrics [CITATION_2] or more general designer-provided annotations [CITATION_3] . Finally, the approximation is checked by a satisfiability procedure for inferring safety or for iteratively refining its precision. With these three pieces it is possible to design sound and relatively complete algorithms for bounded time safety verification that also scale to moderately high-dimensional models [CITATION_4] .",
